.TH BTRFS\-DUMP 1 "March 2026" "btrfs-dump @PROJECT_VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
btrfs\-dump \- dump btrfs filesystem metadata in text format
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B btrfs\-dump
.RB [ \-t | \-\-tree
.IR tree_id ]
.RB [ \-p | \-\-physical ]
.IR device " [" device "...]"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B btrfs\-dump
reads a btrfs filesystem image or device and outputs a text representation
of its metadata trees.
.PP
Only metadata is dumped; file data (both inline and non-inline extents)
is not included in the output.
.PP
If a single device is specified for a multi-device filesystem,
.B btrfs\-dump
will attempt to locate the remaining devices automatically using
.BR blkid (8).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-tree " " \fItree_id\fR
Print only the specified tree. The
.I tree_id
may be a decimal number, a hexadecimal number prefixed with
.BR 0x ,
or a name such as
.BR root ,
.BR extent ,
.BR chunk ,
.BR fs ,
.BR csum ,
.BR uuid ,
.BR free\-space ,
.BR tree\-log ,
.BR remap ,
etc. Names are case-insensitive, and optional
.B btrfs_
prefixes and
.B _tree
or
.B _objectid
suffixes are stripped automatically. The logic here matches that of
.BR "btrfs inspect-internal dump-tree" .
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-physical
Include physical device addresses in tree node headers.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the version string and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-help
Print usage information and exit.
.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
The output is a line-oriented text format. Trees are separated by label
lines ending with a colon (e.g.\&
.BR CHUNK: ,
.BR ROOT: ,
.BR LOG: ,
.BR "Tree 100:" ).
.PP
Trees are dumped in the following order: superblock, bootstrap
(sys_chunk_array), backup roots, chunk tree, remap tree (if present),
root tree, log tree (if present), all other trees, per-subvolume log
trees.
.SS Superblock
.nf
superblock \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ... (dev_item \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...) \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.SS Bootstrap entries
.nf
bootstrap \fIobjectid\fR,type,\fIoffset\fR
chunk_item \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.SS Backup roots
.nf
backup \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.SS Tree nodes
Each tree node begins with a header line, followed by its items:
.PP
.nf
header bytenr=\fIX\fR flags=\fIX\fR generation=\fIX\fR owner=\fIX\fR level=\fIX\fR ...
.fi
.PP
The indentation of a tree is determined by its level.
.PP
Internal node keys include block pointers:
.PP
.nf
\fIobjectid\fR,\fItype\fR,\fIoffset\fR blockptr=\fIX\fR generation=\fIX\fR
.fi
.PP
Leaf items consist of a key line followed by an item data line:
.PP
.nf
\fIobjectid\fR,\fItype\fR,\fIoffset\fR
\fIitem_type\fR \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.PP
All numbers apart from datetimes and file modes are given in hexadecimal. This
is contrary to the behaviour both of \fBbtrfs-progs\fR and the kernel, both of
which near-universally use decimal.
.SS Trailing data
If a recognised item type has trailing bytes beyond the known structure,
they are appended as
.BR " extra=" \fIhex\fR.
Unknown item types are output as
.BI "unknown (size=" X ") extra=" hex\fR.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR btrfs (8),
.BR btrfs\-check (8)
.SH AUTHOR
Written by Mark Harmstone (\fBmark@harmstone.com\fR).
.SH WEB
https://github.com/maharmstone/btrfs-dump
